1 sufficient credible data to grant the request, the department shall provide public notice of its intended action and
2 allow 60 days for public comment prior to taking action on the request. A person aggrieved by the department's
3 decision to grant or deny the request may appeal the department's decision to the board.
4 (4) The department shall, in consultation with local conservation districts and watershed advisory
5 groups pursuant to 75-5-704, review and revise the list and priority rankings of water bodies identified as
6 threatened or impaired. The department shall review and revise the list at intervals not to exceed 5 years. The
7 department shall make available for public review the data and information used in making any changes in its
8 list of threatened or impaired water bodies that is developed and maintained pursuant to this section.
9 (5) By October 1, 1999, and in consultation with the statewide TMDL advisory group established
10 pursuant to subsection (10), the department shall develop and maintain a data management system that can be
11 used to assess the validity and reliability of the data used in the listing and priority ranking process. The
12 department shall make available to the public, upon request, data from its data management system. The
13 department may charge a reasonable fee for the data, commensurate with its cost of providing the data to the
14 requestor.
15 (6) By October 1, 1999, and in consultation with the statewide TMDL advisory group, the
16 department shall use the data management system developed and maintained pursuant to subsection (5) to
17 revise the list and to remove any water body that lacks sufficient credible data to support its listing. If the
18 department removes a water body because there is a lack of sufficient credible data to support its listing, the
19 department shall monitor and assess that water body during the next field season or as soon as possible
20 thereafter to determine whether it is a threatened water body or an impaired water body.
21 (7) Except as provided in subsection (9), in prioritizing water bodies for TMDL development, the
22 department shall, in consultation with the statewide TMDL advisory group, take into consideration the following:
23 (a) the beneficial uses established for a water body;
24 (b) the extent that natural factors over which humans have no control are contributing to any
25 impairment;
26 (c) the impacts to human health and aquatic life;
27 (d) the degree of public interest and support;
28 (e) the character of the pollutant and the severity and magnitude of water quality standard
